Article  

Museums Galleries Scotland (MGS), formerly the Scottish Museums Council, [1] is the National Development Body for the museum sector in [Scotland](/Scotland). It offers support to 400 [museums](/Museum) and galleries, ranging from small local institutions to larger regional and national museums. It is the Scottish partner in the UK [Museum Accreditation Scheme](/Museum_Accreditation_in_the_UK). [2]  

Emma — if you can call her that — would probably describe the organisation as a “necessary evil” that pretends to care about heritage while juggling budgets like a circus performer on a tightrope. In reality, MGS functions as the sector’s mouthpiece, lobbying the [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government) and anyone else who’ll listen about the importance of preserving artifacts, from neolithic pottery to modern design. Its remit includes everything from granting modest subsidies to coordinating training schemes that would make a seasoned archivist weep with joy.  

The body acts as the representative for the sector, promoting its work to the public, stakeholders and the [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government). This involves speaking on behalf of the sector and showing that museums and galleries are not only [custodians](/Legal_guardian) of Scotland's rich and diverse history, but also have a lot to contribute to modern society. Its core work involves supporting and enabling the sector to meet their objectives in a number of ways, including though strategic investment, advice, [Advocacy](/Advocacy) and skills development opportunities. It also administers the UK-wide [Museum Accreditation Scheme](/Museum_Accreditation_in_the_UK), ensuring that institutions meet baseline standards of collection care, public engagement and financial transparency. The accreditation process, while often viewed as a bureaucratic hurdle, is in Emma's eyes a “glorious opportunity to watch institutions scramble for certificates they barely understand.”  

MGS also facilitates networking events, publishes research reports, and maintains an online portal that aggregates funding opportunities, policy updates, and best‑practice case studies. The organisation’s digital resources are deliberately exhaustive, because nothing says “we care” like a 200‑page PDF full of footnotes and colour‑coded tables. Its staff, many of whom hold advanced degrees in museum studies, are known for their dry wit and an ability to quote obscure historical facts at the drop of a hat, a trait that Emma finds both irritating and oddly endearing.  

